'''Nadiem Amiri''' ([[Persian language|Persian]] {{langx|Prs|ندیم امیری}}; born 27 October 1996) is a German professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for {{German football updater|FSVMainz}} club [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] and the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref>{{Soccerway|nadiem-amiri/296416}}</ref> He is considered the greatest footballer of Afghan origin due to his accomplishments in Europe and for playing in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Soccerway|nadiem-amiri/296416}}</ref>

==Early life==
Amiri was born in [[Ludwigshafen]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[Germany]], to Afghan parents.

==Club career==
===TSG Hoffenheim===
Amiri joined [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|TSG Hoffenheim]] in 2012 from [[SV Waldhof Mannheim|Waldhof Mannheim]]. He made his Bundesliga debut on 7 February 2015 in a 3–0 away defeat against [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/02/07/germany/bundesliga/vfl-wolfsburg/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-ev/1713729/|title=Wolfsburg vs. 1899 Hoffenheim|date=7 February 2015|website=Soccerway|publisher=Platform Group|access-date=15 February 2015|archive-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828135845/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/02/07/germany/bundesliga/vfl-wolfsburg/tsg-1899-hoffenheim-ev/1713729/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Amiri recorded his first goal of the [[2015–16 TSG 1899 Hoffenheim season|season]] and for his club in a 3–3 draw against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] on 28 November.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd14n-tsg-1899-hoffenheim-3-3-borussia-moenchengladbach-match-report.jsp|url-status=dead|title=Gladbach fight back to rescue point at Hoffenheim|publisher=Bundesliga|access-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210131120150/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/blmd14n-tsg-1899-hoffenheim-3-3-borussia-moenchengladbach-match-report.jsp|archive-date=31 January 2021}}</ref> On 30 April 2016, he scored the winning goal in the 84th minute during a 2–1 victory against [[FC Ingolstadt 04]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.in/football/report?gameId=426840|title=TSG Hoffenheim 2–1 FC Ingolstadt 04|website=[[ESPN FC]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|access-date=28 August 2018}}</ref> On 12 June 2017, Amiri signed a contract extension with Hoffenheim until 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.achtzehn99.de/newsarchive/news-archive-2017/juni-2017/nadiem-amiri-extends-tsg-contract-until-2020|url-status=dead|title=Nadiem Amiri Extends TSG Contract Until 2020|publisher=TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|website=12 June 2017|access-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627205042/https://www.achtzehn99.de/newsarchive/news-archive-2017/juni-2017/nadiem-amiri-extends-tsg-contract-until-2020|archive-date=27 June 2019}}</ref> On 20 October, Amiri scored a goal in a 3–1 [[2017–18 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] victory against [[İstanbul Başakşehir F.K.]] and sealed his club's first ever victory in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hoffenheim-istanbul-basaksehir-europa-league-line-ups-stats-live-blog-nagelsmann-461800.jsp|url-status=dead|title=Hoffenheim record first ever European win against Basaksehir|website=Bundesliga|access-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019233712/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hoffenheim-istanbul-basaksehir-europa-league-line-ups-stats-live-blog-nagelsmann-461800.jsp|archive-date=19 October 2018}}</ref>

===Bayer Leverkusen and Loan to Genoa===
Amiri signed a five-year contract with [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bayer04.de/en-us/news/bayer04/amiri-joins-the-werkself |title= Amiri joins the Werkself |website=Bayer 04 Leverkusen|date=30 July 2019|access-date=21 July 2025}}</ref>

On 29 January 2022, he joined [[Genoa CFC|Genoa]] in Italy on loan. Genoa would have held an obligation to buy his rights at the end of the loan if certain conditions were met.<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=[[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]|url=https://genoacfc.it/nadiem-amiri-e-un-giocatore-del-genoa/|title=Nadiem Amiri È Un Giocatore Del Genoa|date=29 January 2022|access-date=29 January 2022|language=it|archive-date=15 October 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221015110036/https://genoacfc.it/nadiem-amiri-e-un-giocatore-del-genoa/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In the [[2022–23 Bundesliga]], Amiri played 36 matches in all competitions, in which he scored four goals in the league. In August 2023, Amiri traveled to Leeds ahead of a supposed transfer to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], but it unfortunately collapsed.<ref>{{cite web|first=Axel|last=Hesse|url=https://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/bayer-leverkusen/3x-ja-3x-nein-die-peinlichste-transfer-posse-des-sommers-85217914.bild.html|title=Ex-DFB-Star sorgt für peinliche Wechsel-Posse!|website=[[Bild]]|language=de |date=29 August 2023 }}</ref>

===Mainz===
On 31 January 2024, Amiri signed a 2.5-year contract with [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]].<ref>{{Cite press release|website=Mainz 05|url=https://www.mainz05.de/news/nadiem-amiri-wird-05er|title=Nadiem Amiri Becomes 05er|date=31 January 2024|access-date=31 January 2024|language=de|archive-date=31 January 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131214146/https://www.mainz05.de/news/nadiem-amiri-wird-05er|url-status=live}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Amiri made his debut for [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany under-21]] in March 2016, coming on as a late substitute in a [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|European U21 Championship qualifier]] against [[Russia national under-21 football team|Russia under-21]].<ref name="Bundesliga 2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/afghanistan-refugees-son-hoffenheim-s-nadiem-amiri-not-forgotten-his-roots-466551.jsp|title=Hoffenheim's Nadiem Amiri: the refugees' son who hasn't forgotten his roots|publisher=Bundesliga|date=15 December 2017|access-date=28 August 2018|archive-date=28 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828134304/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/afghanistan-refugees-son-hoffenheim-s-nadiem-amiri-not-forgotten-his-roots-466551.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was part of the Germany under-21 team that won the [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] by defeating [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21]] in the [[2017 UEFA European Under-21 Championship Final|final]].<ref name="Bundesliga 2018"/>

Amiri was selected as one of three overage players for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|Tokyo Olympics]], where he scored in each of [[Germany Olympic football team|Germany]]'s first two games, a defeat to [[Brazil Olympic football team|Brazil]] and a victory against [[Saudi Arabia national under-23 football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Brazil 4-2 Germany: Richarlison scores hat-trick in Brazil's Olympics opener|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12010/12361411/brazil-4-2-germany-richarlison-scores-hat-trick-in-brazils-olympics-opener|website=[[Sky Sports]]|date=22 July 2021|access-date=21 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=10-man Germany beats Saudi Arabia 3-2 in Olympic soccer|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/olympics/10-man-germany-beats-saudi-arabia-3-2-in-olympic-soccer/2021/07/25/d161dd72-ed51-11eb-81b2-9b7061a582d8_story.html|date=22 July 2021|access-date=21 July 2025|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

===Senior===
On 9 October 2019, Amiri made his [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]] debut in a 2–2 [[Exhibition match|friendly]] draw against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], coming on as a substitute to [[Julian Brandt]] in the 66th minute.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Marcus|last=Mühlenbeck|title=Brutales Nationalmannschafts-Geständnis von DFB-Star!|url=https://www.bild.de/sport/fussball/sportstudio-brutales-nationalmannschafts-gestaendnis-von-dfb-star-67f1a2148a9ffe66cb0416ad|website=Bild|date=6 April 2025|access-date=21 July 2025|language=de}}</ref> In March 2025, he was recalled to the team by [[Julian Nagelsmann]] after being absent for more than five years since his last appearance against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nach über vier Jahren: Amiri zurück im DFB-Team|url=https://sport.sky.de/fussball/artikel/amiri-feiert-nach-sky-infos-comeback-im-dfb-team/13327368/34943|website=[[Sky Sport (Germany)|Sky Sport Germany]]|date=12 March 2025|access-date=21 July 2025|language=de}}</ref> Amiri scored his first senior national team goal on 7 September 2025 in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group A|World Cup qualifier]] against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref>https://sports.yahoo.com/article/first-goal-moment-magic-germany-204100240.html</ref> On 21 May 2026, he was selected in Germany’s 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dfb.de/news/bundestrainer-nagelsmann-gibt-wm-kader-bekannt|title=Bundestrainer Nagelsmann gibt WM-Kader bekannt|publisher=[[German Football Association]]|language=de|date=21 May 2026|access-date=21 May 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Amiri was born in [[Ludwigshafen]] to [[Afghans|Afghan]] parents.<ref name="Bundesliga 2018"/> His cousin [[Zubayr Amiri]] and brother Nauwid Amiri also play football.<ref>{{cite web |last=Buschmann |first=Heiko |title=Amiri: Auch Nauwid träumt vom Nationalteam |url=https://www.fussball.de/newsdetail/amiri-auch-nauwid-traeumt-vom-nationalteam/-/article-id/144961#!/ |website=fussball.de |access-date=29 May 2021 |language=de |date=8 May 2016 |archive-date=31 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220131085334/https://www.fussball.de/newsdetail/amiri-auch-nauwid-traeumt-vom-nationalteam/-/article-id/144961#!/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Amiri is sponsored by American sportswear supplier [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nssmag.com/en/sports/19965/nike-helden-just-do-it | title=The new video of the Nike "Just Do It" campaign with Gotze}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Nadiem Amiri Football Boots|url=https://soccerbootsdb.com/player/nadiem-amiri-1030/|url-status=dead|website=Soccer Boots Database|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230604132608/https://soccerbootsdb.com/player/nadiem-amiri-1030/ |archive-date=4 June 2023}}</ref>

